==English==

===Etymology===
First attested circa [[w:17th century|17th century]], alteration of [[huzzah]]. This is however questinable. Another plausible etymology is from mongolian war cry "Urra", which made its way to slavic languages as "Ura" (in 12-13 century) and later to Germanic languages: "hurra" in Germain, Danish, Swedish and Norwegian.

===Interjection===
'''hooray''' ''or'' '''hurray''' ''or'' '''hurrah'''

#Used to express [[approval]], [[joy]] or [[victory]].

====Translation====
*Russian: [[ура]]
*Japanese: [[やった]] (yatta)
*Polish: [[hura]]

===Noun===
'''hooray'''

#A shout to signify victory
#An expression of excitement

===Verb===
'''hooray''' ([[hoorays]], [[hoorayed]], [[hooraying]])

# to shout an expression of excitement

